SUNDAY
FERUARY 5, 1933
Dear Est Debs-
We have been fottunate in escaping several bad storms which have been
reported by other ships to the authorities at Tokyo, but have turned either
North or south waay from us.
Just now however we are in the middle of a very
severe blow. Everything on the ship is tied down and walking is difficult,
unles you have something to hold onto.
They say that we may possibly get in
to Yokohama on Wednesday night instead of Thursday morning as scheduled. My
present plans are to spend a day or two at Tokyo and then catch this same
boat at Kobe, going on to Shanghai, Hong Kong and Manila.
Tonight we are to have some more non-talking "Talkies" in
the shape of "The Girl from Woolworths." We also are engaged in a pingpong
championship which
Groeger and I have both gone into. I have promised him
a gold watch and chain if he wins the tournament. Am reasonably safe because
I can beat him and practically anyone else on the boat can beat me, so his
chances are wht you might say somewhat remote.
I have learned to know most of the other passengers by name
now. There is a Mr. and Mrs. Burke who live in the Philippines and have just
been home to Washington for Christmas. They are very nice but not particularly
interesting.
There is an Englishmen who represents the Shell Petroleum Co., in
Japan, another who sells machinery for a wholesale firm in Manchester, another
who represents the Goodrich Tire, also an American with the Standard Oil Co
at Hong Kong. An Englishman who has lived in Singapore and who I think is a
"barister". One interesting man is the head of an arbacological society at
Singapore. He has lived so long among the Chinese and the Indians that he sits
in a chair with his feet under him, and I suppose would really be more com-
fortable if he could sit on the floor. We call him Ghandi, and he has no small
likness for Ghandi except that he is a few shades whiter and its too darned
cold to get along withba sheet if that is his habit.
